- adding a remote

    # syntax
    $ git remote add <remotename> <remoteurl>

    # e.g. adding a remote we name "origin"
    $ git remote add origin https://github.com/ekoka/tsk.git

    # pushing "master" branch to the "origin" remote
    $ git push origin master


- set remote as upstream

    # to set the remote as the upstream add `--set-upstream | -u` flag during push

    # syntax
    $ git push -u <remote> <localbranch>:<remotebranch>
    $ git push --set-upstream <remote> <localbranch>:<remotebranch>

    # e.g. set "origin" remote as upstream
    $ git push --set-upstream origin master

- setting push.default options

    # check current config
    $ git config --global|--local push.default

    # set config
    git config --global|--local push.default upstream|simple

    upstream: push current branch to its upstream branch
    current: push current branch to branch of same name
    simple: (default) like upstream, but refuses to push if upstream branch name is different from local branch name.


